{{Infobox government agency |agency_name = Naro Space Center |logo = |logo_width = 220px |seal = |seal_width = 220px |picture = |picture_width = 220px |picture_caption = |formed = {{Start date|2009|06|11}} |agency_type = Governmental |parent_agency = [[KARI]] |parent_department = [[Ministry of Science and ICT]] |jurisdiction = [[Government of South Korea|South Korean government]] |headquarters = '''Naro Space Center :''' [[Outer Naro Island]], [[Goheung|Goheung County]], [[South Jeolla Province|Jeollanam-do]] |coordinates = {{coord|34|25|54.72|N|127|32|6.25|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} |employees = 829 (2011) |budget = [[South Korean Won|&#65510;]]298 billion ≈ [[Us dollar|US$]]255 million (2011) |chief1_name = Seung Jo Kim (김승조) |chief1_position = director |chief2_name = Cheol Ho Lim (임철호) |chief2_position = deputy director |chief3_name = Dong Hoon Chung (정동훈) |chief3_position = chief auditor |website = [http://www.kslv.or.kr/naro/naro_ntrd_01.asp?mn=1 Naro Space Center (KARI, KSLV-1)] [http://www.kari.re.kr/data/contents/researchprogram_14111.asp?catcode=1013101100&catcode_value=1013101100&depthno=1&v1_num=3 Naro Space Center (KARI)] |map = |map_width = 220px |map_caption = }}<!-- {{Infobox government agency |agency_name = |headquarters = '''KARI :''' [[Yuseong-gu]], [[Daejeon|Daejeon Metropolitan City]], [[South Korea|Republic of Korea]] |latd=36 |latm=22 |lats=36|longd=127 |longm=21 |longs=21 }} -->{{Infobox Korean name | hangul = 나로우주센터 | hanja = 羅老宇宙센터 | rr = Naro Uju Senteo | mr = Naro Uju Sentŏ }} '''Naro Space Center''' is a [[South Korea]]n [[spaceport]] in [[South Jeolla]]'s [[Goheung|Goheung County]], operated by the state-run [[Korea Aerospace Research Institute]].
The spaceport is located about {{convert|485|km|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} south of [[Seoul]].<ref>[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/techscience/2009/08/20/0601000000AEN20090820004200320.HTML ''Software glitch halts rocket launch'' - Yonhap News Agency]</ref> It includes a launch pad, a control tower, rocket assembly and test facilities, facilities for satellite control testing and assembly, a media center, an electric power station, a space experience hall and a landing field.<ref>''[http://www.spacedaily.com/news/korea-03b.html South Korea Begins Construction Of New Space Center]'' – Korean Information Service, ''SpaceDaily'', August 12, 2003</ref><ref>"Korea to enter space race in 2008", http://www.korea.net/News/News/NewsView.asp?serial_no=20080102014&part=107|, Ro Ji-woong Korea.net Staff Writer, 03 January, 2008, accessed October 28, 2008</ref>
The first launch, initially planned for 19 August 2009, was performed on 25 August 2009 using a Russo-South Korean [[Naro-1]] rocket, but failed to reach the desired orbit. Another rocket launch from Naro was planned for May 2010, but delays pushed the launch to June. On June 10, 2010, this second attempt also ended in failure when the rocket lost communications 137 seconds after launch. The South Korean science minister Ahn Byung-man later told reporters that the rocket was believed to have exploded. A third attempt was made on January 30th 2013 and finally succeeded in putting a satellite into orbit.
South Korea's next rocket, the [[KSLV-2]] is also scheduled to be launched from Naro in 2019.
